title: RedMagic 11 Pro+ | 144Hz Display ¬∑ 120W Charge ¬∑ Liquid-Cooling Beast!
description:
üì± All Key Features & Specs of the RedMagic 11 Pro+

üîπ Display & Design

6.85-inch AMOLED display, resolution ~1216 √ó 2688 pixels. 

144 Hz refresh rate, ultra-smooth gaming visuals. 

High touch-sampling rate (for gaming responsiveness). 

Weight ~230g; size approximately 163.8 √ó 76.5 √ó 8.9 mm. 


üîπ Performance & Hardware

Processor: Snapdragon 8 Elite Gen 5 chipset (3 nm) in several reports. 

RAM & Storage: Up to 24 GB LPDDR5T RAM + up to 1 TB UFS 4.1 Pro storage in some variants. 

Operating system: Android 16 based or upgraded in some markets. 


üîπ Cameras

Rear triple camera setup (typical): 50 MP main (with OIS), + 50 MP ultra-wide, + 2 MP macro. 

Front camera: 16 MP in some listings. 

Video recording up to 8K/30fps in some mentions. 


üîπ Battery & Charging

Battery capacity: ~7,500 mAh in many specs for the Pro+ variant. 

Fast charging: up to 120 W wired in some versions; wireless charging (e.g., 80 W) in some variants. 


üîπ Cooling & Gaming Features

Advanced cooling system: includes ‚Äúliquid-cooling‚Äù (liquid-metal VC chamber) and active cooling fan in some models. 

Tailored for gaming: high refresh display, strong GPU, large battery, gaming features like shoulder buttons in some models. 


üîπ Connectivity & Extras

Dual nano-SIM; full 5G support in many bands. 

In-display fingerprint sensor. 

3.5mm audio jack in some models (useful for gaming) and stereo speakers. 



---

üéØ Why This Phone Stands Out

It combines top-tier performance, large battery capacity, and advanced cooling, targeting heavy gamers.

The 144 Hz display + high refresh touch sampling make it ideal for fast-paced games.

The specs (like 120 W charging, up to 24 GB RAM) place it among the flagship ‚Äúgaming phone‚Äù class.

Gaming-focused features (cooling, performance, display) make it a strong choice for creators or reviewers focusing on high performance.

title: Apple's appearance and craftsmanship are so magical‚Äº Ô∏èMobile phone digital digital technology Apple
How Sharp Went From Pencils To TVs
description:
This lecture will tell the story of the Sharp brand, one of the leaders in technological innovation. We will start with the beginning of Sharp's history when the company produced pencils and go through all stages of its development, including the history of microchips and the evolution of technologies. You will learn how Sharp became one of the leading manufacturers of electronics, including Sharp televisions and other devices. We will also look at interesting facts about Sharp's history, such as the development of the CD changer and remote control, and how the company continues to innovate and push the boundaries of technology. From pencils to LCD televisions, Sharp's history is a fascinating tale of technological achievements and dedication to innovation. Today, Sharp continues to be a leader in the world of electronics, offering products like the Sharp Aquos R9 and shaping technology trends. Join us to learn more about Sharp's history and how this company became one of the most recognized and respected names in the world of technology.

Hello from Valve headquarters! We just saw the Steam Machine, the PC game console that's not much bigger than a box of Kleenex. It's coming alongside the sequel to the Steam Controller, the most customizable gamepad ever made. It's like a Steam Deck for your TV with far more performance -- enough to replace an Xbox or PlayStation in your living room, perhaps? But might be priced more like a PC...

The SmartBand tracks vital signs Like heart rate, blood oxygen Levels, and body temperature in real-time, using advanced sensors and Al algorithms to provide personalized health insights and alerts. title: Valve Steam Machine, Desktop SteamOS, Steam Frame VR, & Controller | ft. Engineering Discussion
description:
SUPPORT THE AI DYSTOPIA REPORT SERIES: https://store.gamersnexus.net/ai-dystopia
Valve today is announcing its Steam Machine, Steam Frame VR headset, and new Steam Controller. Alongside these announcements, the company is moving SteamOS to what is functionally a desktop platform while also adapting it to ARM for the Frame VR headset. The new Steam Controller makes some major iterations on the original, with a particular focus on TMR thumbsticks and connectivity. In this video, we run through the details of Valve's new hardware and interview many of the company's engineers working on the products. Engineering interviews and discussions talk about signal trace routing, power delivery, ESD protections, acoustics, thermals, and more. We have at least two other videos coming up from this visit as well, likely immediately, so subscribe to catch our Steam Frame thermal, power, and acoustics engineering interview next.

It's the hardware we've been waiting for. Built on SteamOS, Valve's brand-new Steam Machine runs the same games that Steam Deck does, with 6x the graphics horsepower - all built into a super-cute, premium, cube-like design.
